WEBVTT

1
00:00.510 --> 00:04.440
- Welcome back to Understanding Quantum
Information and Computation.

2
00:04.440 --> 00:09.900
My name is John Watrous, and I'm the technical director
of Education at IBM Quantum.

3
00:09.900 --> 00:16.290
This is the second lesson of the series. If you haven't already
watched the first lesson, be sure to check it out.

4
00:16.290 --> 00:23.880
We'll be building directly on what we talked about
in the first lesson, so it's important to have an
understanding of that material going into this lesson.

5
00:23.880 --> 00:30.420
Also, be aware that the series
includes textbook content in addition to videos, and you can find a link
to the textbook content

6
00:30.420 --> 00:35.910
in the video description. This is lesson two of
unit one of the series.

7
00:35.910 --> 00:39.840
Unit one covers the basics
of quantum information.

8
00:39.840 --> 00:46.860
In the previous lesson, we talked about quantum information in the setting of single systems, meaning that we have one
system that stores information

9
00:46.860 --> 00:50.790
and we're describing how
it works in isolation.

10
00:50.790 --> 00:57.930
We spent a fair amount of
time on classical information, mainly to establish a point of reference and to highlight the
mathematical similarities

11
00:57.930 --> 01:02.040
between quantum and classical information.

12
01:02.040 --> 01:09.930
We also saw how quantum states can be represented by vectors, specifically vectors having
complex number entries and Euclidean norm equal to one,

13
01:09.930 --> 01:15.368
and we discussed standard
basis measurements and unitary operations.

14
01:15.368 --> 01:21.540
In this lesson, we're gonna expand our
view to multiple systems, each of which is capable of
storing quantum information.

15
01:21.540 --> 01:27.540
This is not simply a matter of saying that each individual system
works as we discussed last time, there is a sense in which the hole

16
01:27.540 --> 01:34.530
is greater than the sum of the parts, and that's also true of
classical information when probabilities are involved.

17
01:34.530 --> 01:41.790
Multiple systems can
interact with one another and they can be correlated
with one another for instance, and in the quantum setting, this includes the possibility

18
01:41.790 --> 01:46.980
that the systems are entangled, which is a term that you
may have heard about before.

19
01:46.980 --> 01:54.780
Entanglement is a very
important phenomenon in quantum information and we'll have a lot more to say about it as the series continues.

20
01:54.780 --> 02:01.860
There is a simple principle, however, that offers us quite a lot of traction for thinking about and
understanding quantum information for multiple systems,

21
02:01.860 --> 02:08.220
and that is that we can always
take two or more systems and put them together or just conceptually
think about them together

22
02:08.220 --> 02:12.270
and view them as if they form
a single compound system.

23
02:12.270 --> 02:20.430
And when we think about a
compound system like this, as if it's a single system, we recognize that it must be described in a way that's consistent
with everything we learned

24
02:20.430 --> 02:23.970
in the previous lesson on single systems.

25
02:23.970 --> 02:31.620
We'll see how this works
and how the description of quantum information
from multiple systems emerges pretty naturally from how it works for single systems

26
02:31.620 --> 02:39.810
based on this one principle. Here's an overview of the lesson and it happens to be identical to the previous lessons overview,

27
02:39.810 --> 02:45.210
but this time our focus
will be on multiple systems rather than single systems.

28
02:45.210 --> 02:51.810
Just like we did in the previous lesson and for exactly the same reasons, we're going to start with
classical information.

29
02:51.810 --> 02:59.310
Once again, we'll see
very close similarities between the way that quantum
and classical information work at a mathematical level.

30
02:59.310 --> 03:05.580
We won't typically focus so
much on classical information or start each lesson in the series with classical information like this.

31
03:05.580 --> 03:11.910
Subsequent lessons will tend to be focused much more exclusively on quantum information and computation.

32
03:11.910 --> 03:18.120
But here at the beginning
this is a sensible approach and it goes back to the idea that thinking about classical information

33
03:18.120 --> 03:23.220
can serve as a valuable source of guidance for understanding quantum information.

34
03:23.220 --> 03:27.720
We're also gonna discuss
the important concept of a tensor product in
this part of the lesson.

35
03:27.720 --> 03:34.470
Tensor products are critically important in quantum information, but they also arise in
the classical setting.

36
03:34.470 --> 03:41.910
Then we'll move on to quantum information and much like in the previous lesson we'll discuss quantum states,
standard basis measurements,

37
03:41.910 --> 03:46.530
and unitary operations this
time for multiple systems.

38
03:46.530 --> 03:51.210
We'll start by talking
about classical states of multiple systems.

39
03:51.210 --> 03:59.370
Recall from the previous
lesson that a classical state of a system is a
configuration of that system that can be recognized and
described unambiguously

40
03:59.370 --> 04:05.610
without any uncertainty or error. And in mathematical terms, when we refer to a classical state set,

41
04:05.610 --> 04:10.050
we just mean a finite and non-empty set.

42
04:10.050 --> 04:16.530
We'll begin our discussion
of multiple systems by supposing that we have
just two systems X and Y.

43
04:16.530 --> 04:23.070
X has some set of classical states which we'll call sigma just
like in the previous lesson, and y has some set of classical states

44
04:23.070 --> 04:29.280
that we'll call gamma. The set sigma and gamma
could be the same set or they could be different,

45
04:29.280 --> 04:38.580
but we're giving them different names, not only because they
could be different sets, but also because it'll help
us to keep things clear if we give them different names.

46
04:38.580 --> 04:46.290
We'll find that it's
pretty easy to generalize this entire discussion from two systems to any number of systems, but
by starting with two systems,

47
04:46.290 --> 04:52.620
we can focus on the fundamental ideas without getting bogged down in details.

